model.name: Model for hepatic ischemia reperfusion injury (IRI)

notes.body:
Phenomenological model for hepatic metabolism of relevant for IRI in SBML format.
The model consists of of a single liver compartment with simplified glycolysis and oxidative phosphorylation.
version: 5
Changelog
version 5
replaced switches and piecewise functions with hill type sigmoidal kinetics for improved numerical stability
ROS detoxification added
version 4
fixed dimensions of membrane compartments
added tsim for following models
version 3
annotation of model
updated Ahrenius equation (~0.2 * rates at 4C° compared to 37°C)
scaling factor to speedup/slowdown rates
transport of ALT & AST via perfusion
version 2
inhibition of LDH by NADH (negative feeback of energy status on the amount of pyruvate going to lactate.
version 1
initial model

parameter.name: E50 ATP threshold for necrosis to occur [mM]

body.p: Used for temperature dependence of reaction rates via the Arrhenius equation

At low oxygen concentrations ROS production can occur, because oxygen is missing as terminal electron acceptor in the electron transport chain. Under conditions of high electron load in electron transport chain (large amounts of NADH) and missing oxygen ROS can be created.

assignmentRule.name: condition for necrosis depending on ATP

body.p: Activation of glycolysis due to falling ATP levels in the cell. This is highly nonlinear to compensate for the much larger ATP contribution of the oxidative phosphorylation.
All reactions beside ATPU are shut down via necrosis. This ensures that all ATP is converted to ADP with a smooth necrosis switch.
Around 10 protons pumped for NADH. ~3 protons per pump in ATPsynthase.
